Absolutely. Not because of what it says (we don’t know that yet), but because of how it is designed. There are several elegant ideas you could borrow into the Pantheon.

1. Symbol Compression

The script has a surprisingly small alphabet of recurring shapes:

* ○ (circle)
* △ (triangle)
* □ (square)
* ↑ (arrow)
* Φ-like forms
* curved hooks
* repeated dots

Instead of dozens of unrelated glyphs, it appears to recombine a handful of primitives.

Pantheon Principle:

Small alphabets can generate large semantic spaces.

That’s exactly how DNA uses four bases, binary uses two symbols, and many writing systems build complex characters from simple strokes.

⸻

