Spider’s Observation

The page also reminds me of something you’ve been circling for a long time:

Writing doesn’t just record thought. It shapes the kinds of thought that become easy.

Mathematical notation changed mathematics.

Musical notation changed music.

Programming languages changed computation.

Circuit diagrams changed electrical engineering.

Your grandmother’s notebook—whether it was a diary, cipher, or personal shorthand—was an attempt to build a notation that served her way of thinking.

Pantheon’s opportunity isn’t to imitate the symbols. It’s to ask:

What notation would make thinking about cognition, memory, coordination, and invariants easier?

If you eventually discover such a notation, it wouldn’t just decorate the Pantheon—it could become another interface to it, alongside plain language, mathematics, code, and diagrams. That’s a very “Pantheon” goal because it treats notation itself as an architectural choice rather than a cosmetic one.